\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Assignment 6 Problem One
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Cai
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
1.
 Find the volume of the following solid.
 The solid lies between planes perpendicular to the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 The cross sections perpendicular to the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis are circular disks whose diameters run from the parabola 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}$
\end_inset

to the parabola 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2-x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shape that is formed by this description is a lemon-shaped object that
 is bounded by the two planes perpendicular to the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 Because the cross-sections are circular disks, we have to calculate the
 area of the disks and to do that we must find the radius.
 Because the curves 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2-x^{2}$
\end_inset

 intersect at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=1$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

, we know that the line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=1$
\end_inset

 slices the shape into two perfect halves.
 Thus the radius of one of the disks can be calculated by subtracting 1
 from the top curve 
\begin_inset Formula $y=2-x^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=1-x^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The volume formula we will use is 
\begin_inset Formula $\int A(x)dx$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A(x)=\pi r^{2}$
\end_inset

 because the cross sections are circular disks, which run perpendicular
 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis.
 Thus for calculating the volume of the shape, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-1}^{1}A(x)dx=\int_{-1}^{1}\pi r^{2}dx=\int_{-1}^{1}\pi(1-x^{2})dx=\pi\int_{-1}^{1}1-2x^{2}+x^{4}dx.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\pi[x-\frac{2}{3}x^{3}+\frac{1}{5}x^{5}]\bigg|_{-1}^{1}=\pi[1-\frac{2}{3}(1)+\frac{1}{5}(1)-(-1-\frac{2}{3}(-1)+\frac{1}{5}(-1)]=\frac{16\pi}{15}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore the volume of the following solid is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{16\pi}{15}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_body
